<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900724-0048</DOCNO><DOCID>900724-0048.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Blackstone, Pompadur Set   Media Investing Venture</HL><DATE>07/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><LP>   Blackstone Group and media investor I. Martin Pompadursaid they formed a joint venture to invest $100 million ofequity capital in domestic and foreign media andentertainnent properties.   The investors are entering the media market at the bottom,which may be to their advantage as buyers. With uncertaintyin the regulatory market and the restrictions on highlyleveraged transactions that characterized the cable industryin the past, for example, cable system sales have slowed to atrickle. Radio and television stations have been hurt by adifficult advertising climate, as have newspapers andmagazines.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;It's really a sluggish time&quot; because of the variousproblems confronting the industry, Mr. Pompadur said, addingthat a number of media properties could be helped with aninfusion of equity and some operating expertise. HenrySilverman, a general partner at the Blackstone investmentfirm, said his group believes it is &quot;a perfect time to getinto the media business&quot; because many operators are facing aliquidity crunch. He said the venture will specifically seekdistressed situations.   Mr. Pompadur is a longtime media executive and investorwho has raised several hundred million dollars since 1983through various public limited partnerships for mediainvestments.   Blackstone's Mr. Silverman said the $100 million will comefrom Blackstone's general pool of funds.</TEXT></DOC>